# Field rows can break before their value when their flat width
# exceeds the available budget. longestAlignedPrefix isolates
# overflowing AllowRowBreak rows into their own single-row
# segments so siblings don't pad to the broken row's wide cell-0
# width. The break only fires when the second cell is atomic -
# that is, its Doc has no internal Group / soft Line / Table that
# could break on its own. The restriction keeps `key: {...}` style
# hugging intact for struct/list values: the value's own Group
# breaks instead of the row.
#
# Braceless chain keys (`a: b: c: val`) are built as a tree of
# nested Groups, one per split point. When the value is also atomic
# it sits inside the deepest Group's Nest, so each split point's
# flat-fit check includes val. Wadler-Lindig's left-to-right rule
# then breaks the outermost Group first and only descends as deep
# as needed. The result: the chain breaks only enough to fit val on
# the chain's last line. When the value is complex (struct/list/
# multi-line string) it stays in a separate cell so its own break
# handles overflow.
#
# All of the above only applies when no infinite-width wrapper is in
# effect. In the relpos variant the surrounding subtree carries
# Newline/NewSection RelPos (the user separated each field with a
# blank line), so the file's body is wrapped in an infinite-width
# scope. Inside it, Groups never break on width - chains, calls, and
# lists all stay flat regardless of how far they overshoot the
# budget. Width-only overflow adds no newlines anywhere; the user
# must put a Newline RelPos inside the chain (or call, or list) to
# opt back into multi-line layout.
-- config --
width: 30
-- in.cue --
short: 1

abcabcabcabcabcabcabcabcabcabcabc: 6

aaaa: bbbb: ccccccccccccccccccc: 7

chain_fits: a: b: c: 8

aaaaaaaaa: bbbbbbbbb: ccccccccc: ddddddddd: 6
-- out/relpos --
short: 1

abcabcabcabcabcabcabcabcabcabcabc: 6

aaaa: bbbb: ccccccccccccccccccc: 7

chain_fits: a: b: c: 8

aaaaaaaaa: bbbbbbbbb: ccccccccc: ddddddddd: 6
-- out/norelpos --
short: 1
abcabcabcabcabcabcabcabcabcabcabc:
	6
aaaa:
	bbbb:
		ccccccccccccccccccc: 7
chain_fits: a: b: c: 8
aaaaaaaaa:
	bbbbbbbbb:
		ccccccccc:
			ddddddddd: 6
